#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_materials.rst:175
msgid ""
"``Range.value_at(r)`` samples the range at the fractional position ``r``: "
"``value_at(0)`` returns ``min``, ``value_at(1)`` returns ``max``, and values"
" in between interpolate linearly. ``r`` is not clamped — outside ``[0, 1]`` "
"the value extrapolates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_materials.rst:182
msgid "**Volume and mass calculation**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_materials.rst:184
msgid ""
"``volume`` is a property and returns a bare number — it carries no unit. The"
" number is the volume in whatever length unit the model was drawn in, cubed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_materials.rst:191
msgid ""
"``mass()`` multiplies the volume by ``<shape>.material.material.density``, "
"which is always measured in kg/m³. Because ``volume`` is unitless, "
"``mass(mass_unit, length_unit)`` takes the output mass unit and the length "
"unit used to interpret the volume. Both are optional and default to *gram* "
"and *millimeter*, respectively. A shape without a material raises a "
"``ValueError``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_materials.rst:193
msgid "Volume read as *mm³*, mass reported in *g* (the defaults):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_materials.rst:200
msgid "The same model read as *in³*, mass reported in *lb*:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_materials.rst:207
msgid ""
"The volume number is identical in both cases — only its interpretation "
"changes. One inch is 25.4 mm, so reading the model in inches makes it 25.4³ "
"≈ 16000 times more massive."
msgstr ""

